S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:name: Scale minimum
S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:definition: The minimum scale at which the object may be used, e.g., for ECDIS presentation.
S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:remarks: The modulus of the scale is indicated, that is 1:1 250 000 is encoded as 1250000.

S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:name: language
S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:definition: The method of human communication, either spoken or written, consisting of the use of words in a structured and conventional way.
S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:remarks: The language is encoded by a 3 character code following ISO 639-2/T.

S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:name: Display Name
S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:definition: A statement expressing if a feature name is to be displayed in certain systemdisplay settings or not.
S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:remarks: Where it is allowable to encode multiple instances of feature name for a single feature instance, only onefeature name instance can indicate that the name is to be displayed (display name set to True).

S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:name: Name
S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:definition: The individual name of a feature.

S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:name: Text
S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:remarks: Should be used, for example, to hold the information that is for short cautionary or explanatory notes. Therefore, text populated in text must not exceed 300 characters. Text may be in English, or in a national language. No formatting of text is possible within text. If formatted text, or text strings exceeding 300 characters, is required, then an alternate concept should be used.

S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:name: Category of sea area
S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:definition: Classification of an area based on its physical characteristics

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: gat
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: a natural or artificial passage or channel through shoals or steep banks, or across a line of banks lying between two channels.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: bank
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: an elevation over which the depth of water is relatively shallow, but normally sufficient for safe surface navigation.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: deep
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: in oceanography, an obsolete term which was generally restricted to depths greater than 6,000 m.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: bay
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: an indentation in the coastline.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: trench
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: a long narrow, characteristically very deep and asymmetrical depression of the sea floor, with relatively steep sides.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: basin
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: a depression, characteristically in the deep sea floor, more or less equidimensional in plan and of variable extent.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Mud Flats
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A level tract of land, as the bed of a dry lake or an area frequently uncovered at low tide. Usually in plural.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: reef
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: rock lying at or near the sea surface that may constitute a hazard to surface navigation.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: ledge
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: a rocky formation continuous with and fringing the shore.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: canyon
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: a relatively narrow, deep depression with steep sides, the bottom of which generally has a continuous slope, developed characteristically on some continental slopes.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: narrows
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: a navigable narrow part of a bay, strait, river, etc.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: shoal
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: an offshore hazard to surface navigation that is composed of unconsolidated material.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: knoll
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: a relatively small isolated elevation of a rounded shape.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: ridge
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: (a) A long, narrow elevation with steep sides. (b) A long, narrow elevation often separating ocean basins. (c) The linked major mid-oceanic mountain systems of global extent.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: seamount
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: a large isolated elevation, greater than 1000m in relief above the sea floor, characteristically of conical form.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: pinnacle
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: any high tower or spire-shaped pillar or rock or coral, alone or cresting a summit. It may extend above the surface of the water. It may or may not be a hazard to surface navigation.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: abyssal plain
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: an extensive, flat, gently sloping or nearly level region at abyssal depths.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: plateau
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: a flat or nearly flat area of considerable extent, dropping off abruptly on one or more sides.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: spur
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: a subordinate elevation, ridge or rise projecting outward from a larger feature.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: shelf
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: a zone adjacent to a continent (or around an island) and extending from the low water line to a depth at which there is usually a marked increase of slope towards oceanic depths.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: trough
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: a long depression of the sea floor characteristically flat bottomed and steep sided and normally shallower than a trench.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: saddle
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: a broad pass, resembling in shape a riding saddle, in a ridge or between contiguous seamounts.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: abyssal hills
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: a tract, on occasion extensive, of low (100-500m) elevations on the deep sea floor.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: apron
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: a gently dipping featureless surface, underlain primarily by sediment, at the base of any steeper slope.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: archipelagic apron
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: a gentle slope with a generally smooth surface on the sea floor, characteristically found around groups of islands or seamounts.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: borderland
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: a region adjacent to a continent, normally occupied by or bordering a shelf, that is highly irregular with depths well in excess of those typical of a shelf.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: continental margin
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: the zone, generally consisting of shelf, slope and rise, separating the continent from the abyssal plain or deep sea floor.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: continental rise
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: a gentle slope rising from the oceanic depths towards the foot of a continental slope.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: escarpment
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: an elongated and comparatively steep slope separating or gently sloping areas.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: fan
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: a relatively smooth, fan-like, depositional feature normally sloping away from the outer termination of a canyon or canyon system.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: fracture zone
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: an extensive linear zone of irregular topography of the sea floor, characterized by steep-sided or asymmetrical ridges, troughs or escarpments.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: gap
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: a narrow break in a ridge or a rise.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: guyot
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: a seamount having a comparatively smooth flat top.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: hill
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: a small isolated elevation (see also abyssal hills).

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: hole
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: a local depression, often steep sided, of the sea floor.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: levee
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: a depositional embankment bordering a canyon, valley or deep-sea channel.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: median valley
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: the axial depression of the mid-oceanic ridge system.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: moat
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: an annular depression that may not be continuous, located at the base of many seamounts, islands and other isolated elevations.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: mountains
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: a large and complex grouping of ridges and seamounts.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: peak
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: a prominent elevation either pointed or of a very limited extent across the summit.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: province
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: a region identifiable by a group of similar physiographic features whose characteristics are markedly in contrast with surrounding areas.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: rise
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: (a) A broad elevation that rises gently and generally smoothly from the sea floor. (b) The linked major mid-oceanic mountain systems of global extent.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: sea channel
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: a continuously sloping, elongated narrow depression commonly found in fans or abyssal plains and customarily bordered by levees on one or both sides.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Seamount Chain
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: Several seamounts in linear or arcuate alignment. Also called: seamounts.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: shelf-edge
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: a narrow zone at the seaward margin of a shelf along which is a marked increase of slope.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: sill
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: a sea floor barrier of relatively shallow depth restricting water movement between basins.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: slope
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: the slope seaward from the shelf edge to the upper edge of a continental rise or the point where there is a general reduction in slope.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: terrace
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: a relatively flat horizontal or gently inclined surface, sometimes long and narrow, which is bounded by a steeper ascending slope on one side and by a steeper descending slope on the opposite side.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: valley
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: a relatively shallow, wide depression, the bottom of which usually has a continuous gradient. This term is generally not used for features that have canyon-like characteristics for a significant portion of their extent.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: canal
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: an artificial water course used for navigation.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: lake
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: a large body of water entirely surrounded by land.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: river
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: a relatively large natural stream of water.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: reach
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: a straight section of a river, especially a navigable river between two bends or an arm of the sea extending into the land

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Intertidal Cay
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A low, flat island of sand, coral, etc. awash or submerged at high water.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Submarine volcano
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: a vent in the earth's crust through which lava, steam, ashes, etc., are expelled, either continuously or at irregular intervals that is located underwater

S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:name: Feature Name
S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:definition: The complex attribute provides the name of an entity, defines the national language of the name, and provides the option to display the name at various system display settings.

S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:name: Information
S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:definition: Textual information about the shape of a non-standard topmark.
S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:remarks: No formatting of text is possible within shape information. If formatted text is required, then an associatedtext file referenced by the complex attribute textual description must be used

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Sea area/named water area
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A geographically defined part of the sea or other navigable waters. It may be specified within its limits by its proper name.
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:remarks: Each sea area is defined independent of any other. Smaller sea areas may be located within larger sea areas.
